<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Hydnum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hydnum subtilior" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="subtilior">Hydnum subtilior</taxonomicName>
is a common species in the southeastern U.S. found in deciduous and mixed forests with a variety of tree associates, often in deep layers of leaf litter. Environmental sequencing has recovered this species from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Quercus" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Quercus</taxonomicName>
root tips in central Mexico (
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia-Guzman, OM" journalOrPublisher="Nucleic Acids Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00572-017-0793-9" year="2017">
<normalizedToken originalValue="García-Guzmán">Garcia-Guzman</normalizedToken>
et al. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). The stipe is usually longer than the diameter of the pileus, and the overall coloration can range from light cream-yellow to peach or tan. The best diagnostic features for this species are the coloration and often elongated stature in combination with broadly ellipsoid spores averaging 8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. In addition, the context of fresh basidiomes stains orange throughout within five minutes when cut in half (Fig. 3H).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
Earlier authors (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Coker and Beers 1951</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Smith et al. 1981</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Harrison, KA" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" pagination="419 - 426" title="Preliminary keys to the terrestrial stipitate Hydnums of North America." volume="28" year="1987">Harrison and Grund 1987</bibRefCitation>
, Roody 2003) referred to this species as 
<taxonomicName genus="H." infraspecific-rank="var." lsidName="H. repandum var. album" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" rank="variety" species="repandum" variety="album">H. repandum var. album</taxonomicName>
, a taxon originally described from Europe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
